    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#oliverioDAI2"/>, p. 114, n. <citedRange>100</citedRange>, fig. 56</bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>9.212</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>025600</citedRange></bibl>. 
                    Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#beschi1970"/>, p. <citedRange>204</citedRange> (date of the base)</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#dthorn-thorn2009"/>, p. <citedRange>140</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#belzic2022"/>, catalogue <citedRange>B.78</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-65183"><name nymRef="#Ξάνθις">Ξάνθις</name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-65381"><name nymRef="#Πολυκλῆς" type="patronymic">Πολυκλεῦς</name></persName></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p>
                    <app loc="1">
                        <rdg resp="#oliverioDAI2 #SEG #fraser-matthews1987 #marengo1991">Ξανθίς</rdg>
                    </app>
               </p>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Xanthis fils de Polyklès.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Xanthis son of Polykles.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Xanthis figlio di Polykles.</p>
            </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>The lettering suggests a date in the 1st half of the third century BC, while Beschi would bring the base down somewhat later.</p>
	   <p>The name <foreign xml:lang="grc">Ξάνθις</foreign> is here more probably a masculine in <foreign xml:lang="grc">-ι-</foreign>, short form of 
	       compound names like <foreign xml:lang="grc">Ξάνθιππος</foreign> and alike, rather than a feminine in <foreign xml:lang="grc">-ίδ-</foreign> 
	       (see <bibl><ptr target="#masson1987"/></bibl>), a type that is not at all common in Cyrenaica.</p>
	<p>The Thorns supposed this base to come from the North Necropolis on the assumption that the Italian archaeologists worked only on the part before 
	World War II.</p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
